1)/* Syntax */

return_type function_name(parameter_list)
{
    // statements

    return value;
}

Example:
int add(int a, int b)
{
    return a + b;
}

#definition
type fname (type arg1, type arg2)
{
    /*Local variables & executable code*/
}

#calling a function
fname(arg1, arg2);

#prototype/declaration
type fname (type, type);



2)/* Function Declaration (Prototype) */

  Sometimes the function is written after main().
  Then we need a declaration.

  #include <stdio.h>

  int add(int, int);

  int main()
  {
      printf("%d", add(4,5));
  }

  int add(int a, int b)
  {
      return a+b;
  }

The declaration tells the compiler:
"Trust me, this function exists later."

3) /* What does void mean? */

void means: This function returns nothing.

Example

void display()
{
    printf("Welcome");
}

You cannot write:

int x = display();

because display() returns no value.

4) /* Parameters vs Arguments */

These terms are often confused.

i)Parameters : Variables in the function definition.

int add(int a, int b)

a and b are parameters.

ii)Arguments : Values supplied during the function call.

add(5,7);

5 and 7 are arguments.

5) /* Local Variables */

Variables declared inside a function.

void test()
{
    int x = 5;
}

x exists only inside test().

Trying to use it outside results in an error.

6) /* Scope */
void test()
{
    int x = 10;
}

int main()
{
    printf("%d", x);
}

Compiler error.
x is not visible in main().

